Testcase code:

For JsonReaderTest.java:

public void testNextLongWithLargeLong() throws IOException {
    JsonReader reader = new JsonReader(new StringReader("[9007199254740993]"));
    reader.beginArray();
    assertEquals(9007199254740993L, reader.nextLong());
    reader.endArray();
}

This should fail in buggy version because when parsing 9007199254740993, it will be PEEKED_NUMBER, and parsed via double, and since double cannot represent it exactly, result != asDouble, throwing NumberFormatException.

In fixed version, it will parse directly as long, so pass.

Similarly for negative: -9007199254740993L.

But to cover both, I can use one testcase with positive and negative, but to minimize, I'll use one with positive.

For MapTest.java:

public void testMapDeserializationWithLargeLongKey() {
    long longKey = 9007199254740993L;
    String json = String.format("{%d:\"value\"}", longKey);
    Type typeOfMap = new TypeToken<Map<Long, String>>() {}.getType();
    Map<Long, String> map = gson.fromJson(json, typeOfMap);
    assertEquals(1, map.size());
    assertTrue(map.containsKey(longKey));
    assertEquals("value", map.get(longKey));
}

This should fail in buggy version for the same reason.

